In your code `var resp =  UrlFetchApp.fetch(url)` will create a [HTTPResponse][1] object. First, you will want to know if the response code is [`200 OK`][2]. To gather that information you should use [`getResponseCode()`][3] and check if it equals to `200`. If that is the case, then you must parse the code. To do that you can first use [`getContentText()`][4] and after that [`parse()`][5]. One example implementation, that is compatible with your code, can be this one:

    if (resp.getResponseCode() == 200) {
      var results = JSON.parse(resp.getContentText());
    }

You can then access to the data referring to that variable and the name of the parameter. For example, you could use `results.code`, `results.token`â€¦ If this explanation doesn&#39;t clarify your question, please ask me again for further help.
   

